# The Plan

Pluto's goal is to be a fast, small, and secure, target independent 
code generation and optimization fromework.

We are going to achieve this goal by adhering to Data-Oriented Design
Principles and implementing the language in Zig.

## Goals

The input to the library:

1. utf-8 source files
2. native zig library
3. c ffi bindings
4. binary pluto-ir

the output of the library:

1. native x86-64 assembly source-files
2. native elf object files
3. binary pluto-ir


### First steps

1. Target Independent Assembly (tia)
  - syntax + semantics
2. Target Independent Intermediate Representation (tiir)
  - in memory representation
3. Target Dependent Intermediate Representation (tdir)
  - (i.e. x86 assembly)
  - in memory representation
4. Serialization
  - serialize/deserialize tia <-> tiir
  - serialize/deserialize asm <-> tdir
5. Translation
  - translate tiir -> tdir

## Design

a program can be thought of as a set of bindings, and a set of attributes for each binding.
Each binding can be a symbol bound to a value. and the attributes define the type, linkage,
alignment, debugging info etc...

in order to keep the language simple and fast to parse we are going to write the grammar to LL(1).

in order to make working with the IR fast and simple we are going to use a fixed length instruction 
encoding in Static Single Assignment form, and the Syntax of the language will be a somewhat direct 
encoding of the instruction format. The attribute information will also be kept in a simple format.
A list of key value pairs. This will be LL(1) and extensible with new keywords without overlapping 
with the source code, and without major refactoring of the compiler.

in order to keep the compiler flexible with respect to optimization and code generation we will use 
a pass style architecture. each optimization can be represented as a pass over the code, and reordering 
passes, adding new passes and modifying existing passes will have a minimal architectural impact on 
other passes. 

in order to support multiple target specific intermediate representations, each target will be defined 
with respect to a common API. This common API boundary will allow the code generator to make decisions 
while abstracted away from the specifics of the intermediate representation. Each target will also 
define a serialization API to both assembly and binary, for the creation of human readable and auditable 
code, as well as for emission into an object file representation.
 


